1
00:00:02,085 --> 00:00:06,255
Good morning and happy, my second
favorite holiday after Christmas,

2
00:00:06,256 --> 00:00:07,548
Development Day every...

3
00:00:07,549 --> 00:00:09,091
Ooh. Donuts. Come on.

4
00:00:09,092 --> 00:00:12,054
Oh, that's nice, but I am cutting today,
so I will just have a yogurt.

5
00:00:12,721 --> 00:00:14,639
Hmm, how am I feeling today, right?

6
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:16,974
Am I feeling sophisticated
or am I feeling nutty?

7
00:00:16,975 --> 00:00:18,434
Am I feeling chocolate frosted?

8
00:00:18,435 --> 00:00:20,144
- Janine.
- [Janine] Oh.

9
00:00:20,145 --> 00:00:23,523
Classic. Thank you.
You know me well, Mel Mel. Hmm.

10
00:00:23,524 --> 00:00:24,899
Well, six years will do that to you.

11
00:00:24,900 --> 00:00:28,069
Oh, did you guys hear
about the ceiling falling in at Addington?

12
00:00:28,070 --> 00:00:30,446
- [Gregory] Mmm.
- And that building was built after ours.

13
00:00:30,447 --> 00:00:31,864
- Really? Wow.
- [Barbara] Mmm.

14
00:00:31,865 --> 00:00:35,368
Morning, y'all. I did get finer.
We don't have to talk about it.

15
00:00:35,369 --> 00:00:37,286
And thanks to whoever
brought in these donuts.

16
00:00:37,287 --> 00:00:39,539
- I thought you did.
- Now, why would I do that?

17
00:00:39,540 --> 00:00:42,083
They were here when I came
to get my coffee this morning.

18
00:00:42,084 --> 00:00:44,835
Hmm. "Donut worry about a thing."

19
00:00:44,836 --> 00:00:46,003
[Jacob] Oh, that place is great.

20
00:00:46,004 --> 00:00:48,339
Remember I brought donuts
for the last day of school last year.

21
00:00:48,340 --> 00:00:49,423
- [Janine] Oh, yeah.
- [Gregory] Oh, yeah.

22
00:00:49,424 --> 00:00:51,342
But none of us got any
because we were determined

23
00:00:51,343 --> 00:00:54,095
to clean our classrooms and get the hell
out of here before rush hour.

24
00:00:54,096 --> 00:00:56,515
[laughing, exclaiming]

25
00:00:58,433 --> 00:00:59,851
[Ava chuckling fades]

26
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:02,521
[spits]

27
00:01:03,939 --> 00:01:05,731
Mr. Johnson, um,

28
00:01:05,732 --> 00:01:07,817
you cleaned out the kitchen
at the end of last year, right?

29
00:01:07,818 --> 00:01:09,610
- Yeah.
- [teachers mumble]

30
00:01:09,611 --> 00:01:12,030
- Wait, did you say last year?
- Yeah.

31
00:01:12,823 --> 00:01:13,823
- Nah.
- [trash bag rustling]

32
00:01:13,824 --> 00:01:14,908
[Ava groans]

33
00:01:16,034 --> 00:01:17,368
Be kidding.

34
00:01:17,369 --> 00:01:20,037
- [Gregory grunts]
- Guys, this year's still gonna be great.

35
00:01:20,038 --> 00:01:22,207
- [loud clattering]
- [Melissa] Whoa!

36
00:01:26,378 --> 00:01:27,379
I wasn't living here.

37
00:01:28,714 --> 00:01:30,007
Ooh, donuts.

38
00:01:32,301 --> 00:01:34,303
[♪ "Hold 'Em" playing]

39
00:01:44,688 --> 00:01:47,274
{\an8}Welcome back lolly? Okay. [chuckles]

40
00:01:47,941 --> 00:01:51,110
{\an8}Y'all know what time it is.
It's Development Day. [chuckles]

41
00:01:51,111 --> 00:01:54,113
Some of the, uh, "grown-ups" are
dreading school starting,

42
00:01:54,114 --> 00:01:58,075
but let me be the first to say
"welcome back" with a lollipop.

43
00:01:58,076 --> 00:01:59,785
{\an8}- Here you go. [chuckles]
- Thank you.

44
00:01:59,786 --> 00:02:00,871
{\an8}Melissa.

45
00:02:02,414 --> 00:02:03,414
{\an8}My lolly.

46
00:02:03,415 --> 00:02:05,791
{\an8}Barbara, you don't want
a welcome-back lollipop, do you?

47
00:02:05,792 --> 00:02:08,712
{\an8}I'd love one. Thank you.

48
00:02:09,254 --> 00:02:11,005
{\an8}[Barbara] <i>Oh, I'm elated to be back.</i>

49
00:02:11,006 --> 00:02:12,840
{\an8}At the end of the last school year,

50
00:02:12,841 --> 00:02:15,551
{\an8}I really found a groove
with the music class,

51
00:02:15,552 --> 00:02:18,846
{\an8}<i>so I spent all summer lesson planning</i>

52
00:02:18,847 --> 00:02:23,184
{\an8}<i>and familiarizing myself with the music
that the students love these days.</i>

53
00:02:23,185 --> 00:02:25,311
{\an8}<i>I've just been re-energized.</i>

54
00:02:25,312 --> 00:02:28,649
It's a new chapter in the book of Barbara.

55
00:02:30,108 --> 00:02:31,942
Can y'all come take a look
at something real quick?

56
00:02:31,943 --> 00:02:33,570
Like this? [grunts]

57
00:02:35,155 --> 00:02:38,116
See we won't be having any fun
this school year. [huffs]

58
00:02:39,743 --> 00:02:41,661
{\an8}Somehow the stove got all out of place.

59
00:02:41,662 --> 00:02:44,163
{\an8}We cannot have the hookups
exposed like that.

60
00:02:44,164 --> 00:02:46,666
{\an8}Not my jurisdiction.
I'll have someone come check it out.

61
00:02:46,667 --> 00:02:48,918
{\an8}Oh, please. [chuckles]
You don't got to call anybody.

62
00:02:48,919 --> 00:02:52,922
{\an8}Step aside. I got this.
It just needs a little... love.

63
00:02:52,923 --> 00:02:55,384
The rumors are true. I'm in love.

64
00:02:56,051 --> 00:02:58,135
His name is O'Shon, and he works in tech.

65
00:02:58,136 --> 00:03:02,098
You know, when we first started dating,
everybody was against us.

66
00:03:02,099 --> 00:03:04,975
The district even fired me
to try to break up our relationship,

67
00:03:04,976 --> 00:03:07,561
and Janine tried to keep me
from getting my job back.

68
00:03:07,562 --> 00:03:11,649
But... [chuckles] ...in spite of it all,
we... we made it through.

69
00:03:11,650 --> 00:03:14,193
{\an8}[♪ presentation playing
moving, emotional music]

70
00:03:14,194 --> 00:03:15,278
{\an8}[Ava chuckles]

71
00:03:16,279 --> 00:03:21,409
{\an8}In summary, I go above and beyond
because I'm in love and O'Shoned.

72
00:03:21,410 --> 00:03:24,453
{\an8}Ava, for the dozenth time,
you really shouldn't show us that stuff.

73
00:03:24,454 --> 00:03:26,205
{\an8}It is an HR violation.

74
00:03:26,206 --> 00:03:27,290
{\an8}So is your shirt.

75
00:03:27,874 --> 00:03:31,502
{\an8}Okay. What else? New counselor coming.
Boring. [inhales sharply]

76
00:03:31,503 --> 00:03:36,174
{\an8}Oh. Everyone, please welcome our new
fourth-grade teacher, Dominic Clark.

77
00:03:41,763 --> 00:03:42,930
Where do I know that name...

78
00:03:42,931 --> 00:03:44,390
{\an8}- I don't know.
- Dominic Clark.

79
00:03:44,391 --> 00:03:50,771
{\an8}Did you star in that new Tyler Perry movie
<i>Madea's Destination Wedding</i>?

80
00:03:50,772 --> 00:03:53,482
{\an8}No, Mrs. Howard. It's me Dominic.
I was in your kindergarten class.

81
00:03:53,483 --> 00:03:59,822
{\an8}[gasps] Dominic, how could I forget?
You colored everything red.

82
00:03:59,823 --> 00:04:02,366
Still do. I'm just playing.
I don't do that anymore.

83
00:04:02,367 --> 00:04:03,826
[staff laughing]

84
00:04:03,827 --> 00:04:05,536
It's just an honor
to be your new colleague.

85
00:04:05,537 --> 00:04:07,121
My new colleague.

86
00:04:07,122 --> 00:04:08,789
- Hi, everyone.
- Hey, how you doing?

87
00:04:08,790 --> 00:04:10,500
Wow, imagine that.

88
00:04:11,168 --> 00:04:16,465
My kindergarten student of nearly, whoo,
20 years ago is my new colleague.

89
00:04:17,007 --> 00:04:20,009
Which is crazy, Barbara,
because you guys look the exact same age.

90
00:04:20,010 --> 00:04:21,218
Yes, we do. Uh...

91
00:04:21,219 --> 00:04:24,263
{\an8}This is not gonna be good.
This is a minefield, okay?

92
00:04:24,264 --> 00:04:28,017
That guy is gonna set Barbara
back to old grumpy Barb.

93
00:04:28,018 --> 00:04:29,935
Yeah, no, I'm on this.

94
00:04:29,936 --> 00:04:32,772
All right. Due to an increase
in middle school students,

95
00:04:32,773 --> 00:04:35,775
Ms. Schemmenti will no
longer be teaching second grade.

96
00:04:35,776 --> 00:04:38,986
She'll be moving up
to teach middle school math in homeroom.

97
00:04:38,987 --> 00:04:40,196
[staff exclaiming]

98
00:04:40,197 --> 00:04:42,449
No, no, it's all right. I already knew.

99
00:04:42,991 --> 00:04:45,534
And, you know, every app is
like sports betting these days,

100
00:04:45,535 --> 00:04:49,622
so I figured that this is an opportunity
for me to refresh my percentages skills.

101
00:04:49,623 --> 00:04:52,166
And since there aren't enough
second graders for two classes,

102
00:04:52,167 --> 00:04:54,794
- Ms. Teagues will now have 40 students.
- [staff exclaiming]

103
00:04:54,795 --> 00:04:57,129
I, for one, am excited
to see if it will break her. [chuckles]

104
00:04:57,130 --> 00:04:58,464
It won't.

105
00:04:58,465 --> 00:05:00,299
- It might.
- Okay, now you're just doing crowd work.

106
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:02,051
We're gonna go finish
setting up our classrooms.

107
00:05:02,052 --> 00:05:04,553
Yep, Development Day over. Good job, team.

108
00:05:04,554 --> 00:05:06,972
Well, did someone say "team"?

109
00:05:06,973 --> 00:05:09,266
- Who's the suit?
- [Ava] Oh. Right.

110
00:05:09,267 --> 00:05:13,271
This paper skeleton is Craig.
The district sent him for some reason.

111
00:05:14,356 --> 00:05:18,984
Uh, yes. Good morning,
Abbott Elementary, and welcome back.

112
00:05:18,985 --> 00:05:21,446
- All right!
- There it is.

113
00:05:22,072 --> 00:05:25,367
Uh, Principal Coleman is right.
I am here for a reason.

114
00:05:25,909 --> 00:05:29,745
The district thinks Abbott is
a very special school,

115
00:05:29,746 --> 00:05:32,540
and we wanted to make it more special

116
00:05:32,541 --> 00:05:35,876
by reaffirming
some core district principles

117
00:05:35,877 --> 00:05:40,548
and moral guidelines
through team building.

118
00:05:40,549 --> 00:05:42,591
- [staff groaning]
- This is a result

119
00:05:42,592 --> 00:05:46,679
of their no-longer-trusting-us
because of last year's lying.

120
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:48,138
Extortion of businesses.

121
00:05:48,139 --> 00:05:51,475
Yep, and our annual tradition
of unpermitted shows and festivities.

122
00:05:51,476 --> 00:05:53,352
Maybe. Yes.

123
00:05:53,353 --> 00:05:56,605
So, this is a punishment couched
in team building activities?

124
00:05:56,606 --> 00:05:59,942
Yes. To show we're all one big team

125
00:05:59,943 --> 00:06:02,987
and rebuild the trust
between the district and Abbott

126
00:06:02,988 --> 00:06:05,114
that you all shattered,

127
00:06:05,115 --> 00:06:10,995
I will be leading everyone in a day
of mandatory team building activities.

128
00:06:10,996 --> 00:06:12,955
So without further ado,

129
00:06:12,956 --> 00:06:17,918
let's all obligatorily
scoot to the library.

130
00:06:17,919 --> 00:06:19,420
- [Craig] Whoo.
- [staff groaning]

131
00:06:19,421 --> 00:06:24,425
Oh, come on, everybody.
A few team building games might be fun.

132
00:06:24,426 --> 00:06:27,387
Oh, not games, activities.

133
00:06:28,430 --> 00:06:31,432
So, when I was in your
kindergarten class 20 years ago--

134
00:06:31,433 --> 00:06:32,850
Let me stop you right there, Dominic.

135
00:06:32,851 --> 00:06:36,896
Oh. Uh-oh. Here we go.
Um, hey, Dom, you should probably--

136
00:06:36,897 --> 00:06:38,815
You know, I'm trying to keep my cool.

137
00:06:40,066 --> 00:06:42,360
But you got me so excited.

138
00:06:42,944 --> 00:06:48,699
My former student is now my colleague.
Oh, what a blessed day to be alive.

139
00:06:48,700 --> 00:06:49,784
- Yes!
- Hey, poindexter.

140
00:06:50,368 --> 00:06:54,246
Whatever this is, can we hurry it up?
Some of us got real jobs to get back to.

141
00:06:54,247 --> 00:06:55,414
Yeah, okay.

142
00:06:55,415 --> 00:06:56,874
Uh, to start us off,

143
00:06:56,875 --> 00:06:59,960
you're gonna share
something people know about you,

144
00:06:59,961 --> 00:07:01,253
and something they don't.

145
00:07:01,254 --> 00:07:02,630
So, I'll start.

146
00:07:02,631 --> 00:07:07,426
Uh, something people do know
about me is that I love my job.

147
00:07:07,427 --> 00:07:08,510
[staff groaning]

148
00:07:08,511 --> 00:07:10,846
Uh, something you don't know is

149
00:07:10,847 --> 00:07:15,059
that I wear a cross,
but I don't believe in God.

150
00:07:15,060 --> 00:07:17,646
But he believes in you.

151
00:07:18,730 --> 00:07:22,816
I'm Barbara Howard,
and one thing you all know about me is

152
00:07:22,817 --> 00:07:28,281
I have a very strong and loving
relationship with God and Gerald.

153
00:07:28,990 --> 00:07:33,369
Oh, but one thing you don't know is
I never use the Lord's name in vain.

154
00:07:33,370 --> 00:07:34,454
Mm-mmm.

155
00:07:35,330 --> 00:07:36,373
Melissa.

156
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:38,957
- Sweet baby Jesus...
- It doesn't count 'cause it's a baby.

157
00:07:38,958 --> 00:07:40,542
[Melissa] So, sure.

158
00:07:40,543 --> 00:07:43,128
Uh, something that you know about me is

159
00:07:43,129 --> 00:07:46,215
you already know everything
you need to know about me.

160
00:07:46,216 --> 00:07:50,177
Something you might not know about me is
that I will smack you in the mouth.

161
00:07:50,178 --> 00:07:51,262
Okay.

162
00:07:52,055 --> 00:07:53,264
Uh, Mr. Johnson.

163
00:07:54,557 --> 00:07:58,560
Something you know about me is
I used to work at Chippendales.

164
00:07:58,561 --> 00:07:59,937
Hey, hey, hey.

165
00:07:59,938 --> 00:08:02,232
Something you don't know is
I swam an entire triathlon.

166
00:08:02,774 --> 00:08:05,359
- Well, that's just an "athalon."
- Wait, why swam?

167
00:08:05,360 --> 00:08:06,736
Easier than riding a kite.

168
00:08:07,529 --> 00:08:08,696
I think you mean a bike.

169
00:08:08,697 --> 00:08:11,323
I wouldn't know. Never rode one.
That's why I swam the whole thing.

170
00:08:11,324 --> 00:08:12,574
What do you mean you never rode one?

171
00:08:12,575 --> 00:08:14,576
You have a Tour de France trophy
in your closet.

172
00:08:14,577 --> 00:08:15,661
[Mr. Johnson] That's for culture,

173
00:08:15,662 --> 00:08:19,289
which you'd know if you...
if you took the time to admire it.

174
00:08:19,290 --> 00:08:22,543
I'm sorry to interrupt,
but w-what's that smell?

175
00:08:22,544 --> 00:08:24,963
- [Jacob] I love this game. [chuckles]
- [Janine] Oh, yeah.

176
00:08:25,463 --> 00:08:27,047
Uh, it smells like dead squirrel.

177
00:08:27,048 --> 00:08:28,173
- [Janine] Ah, y-yeah.
- No, it's raccoons.

178
00:08:28,174 --> 00:08:29,466
- It's raccoons.
- [Jacob] Oh, no.

179
00:08:29,467 --> 00:08:32,928
I... I know what that smell is. It's Morton.
[laughs]

180
00:08:32,929 --> 00:08:34,013
It's not me.

181
00:08:34,723 --> 00:08:36,056
Although it does smell like gas.

182
00:08:36,057 --> 00:08:38,600
I told you a professional needs
to look at that stove.

183
00:08:38,601 --> 00:08:42,062
[scoffs] Probably is Morton's nasty ass,

184
00:08:42,063 --> 00:08:43,481
but I'll go check it out.

185
00:08:47,485 --> 00:08:50,739
Well, I smell a little somethin'-somethin'
but nothing too crazy, right?

186
00:08:54,159 --> 00:08:55,326
Right?

187
00:09:00,331 --> 00:09:01,458
Oh, damn.

188
00:09:02,667 --> 00:09:03,835
Oh, damn!

189
00:09:04,711 --> 00:09:06,462
Okay, who would like to go next?

190
00:09:06,463 --> 00:09:09,257
Nobody panic, but I'm gonna need
everybody to leave with love.

191
00:09:09,758 --> 00:09:12,259
Outside. Immediately, lovingly.

192
00:09:12,260 --> 00:09:13,510
Did I mention I was in love?

193
00:09:13,511 --> 00:09:14,845
Who else got something to live for?

194
00:09:14,846 --> 00:09:16,264
- What?
- [Melissa] Let's go. Come on.

195
00:09:17,348 --> 00:09:22,144
All right. So, the district will have
someone out here to fix the gas leak,

196
00:09:22,145 --> 00:09:23,979
but what it won't be able to fix is

197
00:09:23,980 --> 00:09:27,441
the fractured moral infrastructure
of this school.

198
00:09:27,442 --> 00:09:29,985
Now, split up into five groups.

199
00:09:29,986 --> 00:09:34,323
Each one will have a different activity
that I will walk you through.

200
00:09:34,324 --> 00:09:37,326
- [groaning]
- Look, the sooner we finish this,

201
00:09:37,327 --> 00:09:39,996
the sooner you'll be able
to get back to your day.

202
00:09:40,497 --> 00:09:42,873
All right, so what is this?
Some kind of metaphor

203
00:09:42,874 --> 00:09:45,042
about how we need
to jump-start our school year?

204
00:09:45,043 --> 00:09:47,753
No, I just didn't realize
how many people there would be,

205
00:09:47,754 --> 00:09:49,047
and those were in my trunk.

206
00:09:52,884 --> 00:09:56,011
You are welcome to come to me
with any problem or concern.

207
00:09:56,012 --> 00:09:58,347
Big or small, I am here to help.

208
00:09:58,348 --> 00:10:00,099
She does have an office hour though.

209
00:10:00,100 --> 00:10:03,852
So, you might wanna, you know, store
a bunch of problems over several weeks.

210
00:10:03,853 --> 00:10:07,148
But if I'm in the office,
those hours are open.

211
00:10:07,649 --> 00:10:09,566
In fact, let me just give you my cell.

212
00:10:09,567 --> 00:10:12,320
What the heck?
Just giving that sucker away for free?

213
00:10:13,154 --> 00:10:14,154
What?

214
00:10:14,155 --> 00:10:17,032
You mad 'cause your real mom left you,
and now your fake mom is leaving you too?

215
00:10:17,033 --> 00:10:18,743
- [Ava chuckles]
- No, it's just...

216
00:10:20,411 --> 00:10:22,247
Barb's all happy now, which is great,

217
00:10:22,747 --> 00:10:25,458
but this guy is getting the Barb
I had to work three years for.

218
00:10:26,084 --> 00:10:28,794
Besides, I'm supposed to be the recipient
to her mentorship, you know.

219
00:10:28,795 --> 00:10:30,796
The up-and-comer to her veteran ways.

220
00:10:30,797 --> 00:10:34,633
The Scrappy-Doo to her Scoobs.
Now, he's Scrappy? I just...

221
00:10:34,634 --> 00:10:35,968
Ooh!

222
00:10:35,969 --> 00:10:41,431
Way to go, hoopers. A fun new wrinkle is
to try with your eyes closed.

223
00:10:41,432 --> 00:10:44,101
And what else is left up for grabs
in the Mystery Gang, you know?

224
00:10:44,102 --> 00:10:49,523
Because Gregory's Fred,
and Jacob is Velma, and Melissa's Daphne.

225
00:10:49,524 --> 00:10:53,777
I'm Daphne. Oh, my God, Janine.
Your perception is damningly awful.

226
00:10:53,778 --> 00:10:56,114
My point is, who am I at Abbott now?

227
00:10:58,032 --> 00:10:59,033
Who am I?

228
00:11:00,785 --> 00:11:04,664
Hey. You know, I was thinking
about what you said about the triathlon.

229
00:11:05,582 --> 00:11:08,459
- You really can't ride a bike?
- Never had time to learn.

230
00:11:09,335 --> 00:11:11,378
That is wild.
You've lived such a full life.

231
00:11:11,379 --> 00:11:13,673
I just don't know
how riding a bike got skipped over.

232
00:11:14,257 --> 00:11:15,592
I worked a lot as a kid.

233
00:11:16,467 --> 00:11:19,012
Well, if you want,
I can teach you how to ride a bike.

234
00:11:19,512 --> 00:11:21,138
- It's never too late to learn.
- [scoffs, sighs]

235
00:11:21,139 --> 00:11:23,724
- What about your group?
- They're fine.

236
00:11:23,725 --> 00:11:26,852
Gregory, um, which direction do I turn?

237
00:11:26,853 --> 00:11:28,478
Uh, Gregory?

238
00:11:28,479 --> 00:11:29,980
Middle schoolers, huh?

239
00:11:29,981 --> 00:11:32,399
Surprised you didn't mention it
all summer since, you know,

240
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:34,735
I teach middle school
and, well, we live together,

241
00:11:34,736 --> 00:11:36,111
so we see each other every day.

242
00:11:36,112 --> 00:11:38,614
Well, what's to mention? Kids are kids.
The only difference is the math.

243
00:11:38,615 --> 00:11:40,657
I spent the summer learning
to do that, so...

244
00:11:40,658 --> 00:11:42,868
Well, there's a lot more
to it than math, okay?

245
00:11:42,869 --> 00:11:46,038
Preteens are very different
than second graders.

246
00:11:46,039 --> 00:11:48,791
Uh, not really.
Just add a few years and puberty.

247
00:11:49,417 --> 00:11:51,043
I talk to the older girls all the time.

248
00:11:51,044 --> 00:11:55,672
Talking is great. Talking is fun.
But teaching... [chuckles]

249
00:11:55,673 --> 00:11:59,259
The second you become their teacher,
you become their enemy. Right, Morton?

250
00:11:59,260 --> 00:12:00,720
They're gonna eat you alive.

251
00:12:01,554 --> 00:12:05,182
Okay, no offense,
but this sounds like a you two problem.

252
00:12:05,183 --> 00:12:09,728
Okay, well,
you have no idea what they're capable of.

253
00:12:09,729 --> 00:12:11,689
Yeah, you want a taste?

254
00:12:12,690 --> 00:12:15,902
Aight, gross, but yeah. Do your worst.

255
00:12:16,486 --> 00:12:21,240
Yeah! Craig, we finished in what
I can only imagine is record time.

256
00:12:21,241 --> 00:12:24,243
Amazing.
You'll never guess what level two is.

257
00:12:24,244 --> 00:12:26,161
Don't tell me. It's reverse.

258
00:12:26,162 --> 00:12:27,537
It's reverse.

259
00:12:27,538 --> 00:12:31,291
Yeah! Look alive, people.
Reverse, reverse.

260
00:12:31,292 --> 00:12:34,253
Okay. So, I'm young enough
to be the ingenue,

261
00:12:34,254 --> 00:12:35,796
but that's been usurped.

262
00:12:35,797 --> 00:12:38,967
Barbara's doing
the optimistic-and-positive thing.

263
00:12:40,343 --> 00:12:43,345
There's not a grump on the first floor.
I could be the downstairs grump.

264
00:12:43,346 --> 00:12:46,265
Now see, if you had a better personality,
you wouldn't have to search for one.

265
00:12:46,266 --> 00:12:48,268
[chuckles]
You could use that time to find a man.

266
00:12:48,851 --> 00:12:51,020
Okay, you know that I'm dating Gregory.

267
00:12:51,938 --> 00:12:53,355
That's still happening? [chuckles]

268
00:12:53,356 --> 00:12:56,066
Sorry, I haven't been able to keep up
ever since I started dating

269
00:12:56,067 --> 00:12:59,570
the world's only real man, O'Shon.
[chuckles]

270
00:13:00,196 --> 00:13:01,906
Good for you. No one cares. [chuckles]

271
00:13:02,824 --> 00:13:04,700
[stammers] That was my attempt
at being a grump.

272
00:13:04,701 --> 00:13:06,286
I may have overshot it a bit.

273
00:13:06,869 --> 00:13:09,705
All right. I got us a bike.

274
00:13:09,706 --> 00:13:11,540
Okay, Mr. Johnson, get on up here.

275
00:13:11,541 --> 00:13:13,917
Maybe not right now.
My knees aren't feeling so good.

276
00:13:13,918 --> 00:13:15,877
It's actually better
for your knees than walking.

277
00:13:15,878 --> 00:13:18,589
Well, I forgot my baseball card
to put in the spokes.

278
00:13:21,217 --> 00:13:22,968
All right, come on, no excuses, okay?

279
00:13:22,969 --> 00:13:25,262
I'll even hold on
until you get the hang of it.

280
00:13:25,263 --> 00:13:29,058
- [sighs]
- Okay? Here we go. Yeah, there you go.

281
00:13:30,143 --> 00:13:32,436
All right, there it is.

282
00:13:32,437 --> 00:13:34,856
- Promise not to let go.
- I promise.

283
00:13:36,607 --> 00:13:37,608
Okay.

284
00:13:38,276 --> 00:13:39,234
Pinky promise?

285
00:13:39,235 --> 00:13:41,111
Well, I can't now,
I'm holding on to the bike.

286
00:13:41,112 --> 00:13:42,196
[Melissa clicks tongue]

287
00:13:42,822 --> 00:13:44,698
Look, these kids are mean.

288
00:13:44,699 --> 00:13:47,117
One told me,
"That's why your bitch left you, bitch."

289
00:13:47,118 --> 00:13:49,453
I think you're overdoing it on the B-word.

290
00:13:49,454 --> 00:13:50,871
I don't think he's doing it enough.

291
00:13:50,872 --> 00:13:53,123
Hey, why'd you rat out your brother
and get him locked up?

292
00:13:53,124 --> 00:13:54,833
What? That never happened.

293
00:13:54,834 --> 00:13:56,668
And scene. I was being a kid.

294
00:13:56,669 --> 00:14:00,088
We live in a post-truth landscape
and these kids hit below the belt.

295
00:14:00,089 --> 00:14:02,591
Which is where you haven't been touched
in years, snitch,

296
00:14:02,592 --> 00:14:03,675
unless you count Sweet Cheeks.

297
00:14:03,676 --> 00:14:06,136
You keep my son's name
out your filthy mouth.

298
00:14:06,137 --> 00:14:09,264
And don't even think about talking back
to them, or you will get written up.

299
00:14:09,265 --> 00:14:11,725
Every day is
like an episode of <i>Scared Straight!</i>

300
00:14:11,726 --> 00:14:12,809
Take your shoes off!

301
00:14:12,810 --> 00:14:15,521
- Okay, who are we in this scenario?
- Everyone.

302
00:14:17,106 --> 00:14:18,106
You still got me?

303
00:14:18,107 --> 00:14:19,524
Hey, I got you. I got you.

304
00:14:19,525 --> 00:14:21,693
And you have to handle
all of this while teaching. [chuckles]

305
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:25,280
And if even one kid gets the best of you,
that could be a wrap for the period.

306
00:14:25,281 --> 00:14:27,115
- Or the year.
- Oh, no. Uh-uh.

307
00:14:27,116 --> 00:14:28,742
These kids are gonna... [bleep] ...respect me.

308
00:14:28,743 --> 00:14:30,744
Uh-uh, don't curse. They will report ya.

309
00:14:30,745 --> 00:14:33,497
- Yeah, I'll... [bleep] ...report you.
- He just cursed.

310
00:14:33,498 --> 00:14:35,499
He can do that, you see.
He's a little boy.

311
00:14:35,500 --> 00:14:37,542
Actually, I'm a little girl.
You ain't hard, homey!

312
00:14:37,543 --> 00:14:39,836
- Okay.
- [Jacob] That's right. You ain't hard.

313
00:14:39,837 --> 00:14:41,588
Just keep moving forward!

314
00:14:41,589 --> 00:14:43,256
- What?
- You're doing great!

315
00:14:43,257 --> 00:14:44,800
- Eight.
- Eh, a seven.

316
00:14:44,801 --> 00:14:47,052
- What are we doing now?
- Rating you to your face.

317
00:14:47,053 --> 00:14:50,430
Have you ever been called a one
on a day you just knew you were a ten?

318
00:14:50,431 --> 00:14:52,140
- You're a one!
- One.

319
00:14:52,141 --> 00:14:53,683
- One!
- Okay, stop it!

320
00:14:53,684 --> 00:14:55,393
- Stop!
- [Dominic] Stop?

321
00:14:55,394 --> 00:14:57,187
[Tasha] No, no, no.
Don't stop. Walk forward.

322
00:14:57,188 --> 00:14:59,272
- There you go. You got it.
- No, I told you...

323
00:14:59,273 --> 00:15:00,732
- Turn left!
- [Dominic] Left?

324
00:15:00,733 --> 00:15:03,276
[Tasha] No, no, no. Go-Go right.
Go right! No, that...

325
00:15:03,277 --> 00:15:04,736
- [Mr. Johnson clatters]
- [car alarm blaring]

326
00:15:04,737 --> 00:15:06,114
[Mr. Johnson yells, groans]

327
00:15:06,864 --> 00:15:09,741
You promised.
You promised you wouldn't let me fall.

328
00:15:09,742 --> 00:15:10,826
- [Janine inhales sharply]
- [car alarm continues]

329
00:15:10,827 --> 00:15:13,745
[sighs]
Looks like we're gonna be here all day.

330
00:15:13,746 --> 00:15:15,288
Mm-mmm-mmm.

331
00:15:15,289 --> 00:15:17,415
New year, same old Abbott.

332
00:15:17,416 --> 00:15:21,462
Mm-mmm... No, just at the top.
I don't have to do it twice.

333
00:15:23,256 --> 00:15:24,924
You a organ donor, Gregory?

334
00:15:25,925 --> 00:15:27,634
- Why?
- 'Cause whatever I break,

335
00:15:27,635 --> 00:15:30,554
you're gonna donate to me,
and I like those shoulders, Gregory.

336
00:15:30,555 --> 00:15:33,598
Well, today was supposed
to be about building trust

337
00:15:33,599 --> 00:15:35,725
and working together as a team,

338
00:15:35,726 --> 00:15:39,104
and the only thing
you accomplished together is

339
00:15:39,105 --> 00:15:41,064
how to fail in unique ways.

340
00:15:41,065 --> 00:15:42,315
Progress.

341
00:15:42,316 --> 00:15:45,026
And now you get to start over
and do it again.

342
00:15:45,027 --> 00:15:48,155
- [staff groaning]
- Well, I, for one, can't stand this.

343
00:15:48,156 --> 00:15:49,740
Right? 'Cause this guy sucks.

344
00:15:50,324 --> 00:15:53,660
You all suck.
And this whole day sucks, right, guys?

345
00:15:53,661 --> 00:15:56,788
Well, it may suck,
but if we don't finish today,

346
00:15:56,789 --> 00:15:59,666
- we can always come back on the weekend.
- [staff gasping, muttering]

347
00:15:59,667 --> 00:16:01,960
- No.
- [Craig] Oh, okay.

348
00:16:01,961 --> 00:16:04,087
Hey, Ava, listen up. Um...

349
00:16:04,088 --> 00:16:06,631
You know, I was thinking
about this whole grade switch thing,

350
00:16:06,632 --> 00:16:09,801
and I think it might be better
if Janine did the swap instead of me,

351
00:16:09,802 --> 00:16:12,679
'cause, uh, Sweet Cheeks is
afraid of heights,

352
00:16:12,680 --> 00:16:15,891
so for him it's ground floor or nothing.

353
00:16:15,892 --> 00:16:19,562
Um, no, guinea pigs are from the Andes.
They're not afraid of heights.

354
00:16:20,188 --> 00:16:22,231
All right, listen. I...

355
00:16:23,983 --> 00:16:29,279
A change this big, I just don't know
if I'm, like, exactly up for it.

356
00:16:29,280 --> 00:16:30,364
[sighs]

357
00:16:30,948 --> 00:16:34,576
"Zero problem whatsoever. Bring it on.

358
00:16:34,577 --> 00:16:37,245
Those kids are about to get
a lesson in learning lessons,

359
00:16:37,246 --> 00:16:38,623
and you can quote me on that."

360
00:16:39,290 --> 00:16:41,584
That's what you said in June
when I asked you about this.

361
00:16:42,168 --> 00:16:44,587
There's no going back.
Here, this will cheer you up.

362
00:16:46,631 --> 00:16:49,675
- That's O'Shon shirtless in Wildwood.
- It is.

363
00:16:50,593 --> 00:16:52,135
No, actually it kinda helps.

364
00:16:52,136 --> 00:16:55,347
- It sure does. [chuckles]
- Good job.

365
00:16:55,348 --> 00:16:58,225
Hey, Mel. So, about before...

366
00:16:58,226 --> 00:17:01,853
You were totally busting my chops
about how the sixth graders act, right?

367
00:17:01,854 --> 00:17:03,564
- I knew it.
- [Mr. Morton] No, we weren't.

368
00:17:04,148 --> 00:17:07,360
And those were just the experiences
that I haven't repressed yet.

369
00:17:08,069 --> 00:17:09,194
Morton...

370
00:17:09,195 --> 00:17:10,947
[stammers] Sorry.

371
00:17:11,489 --> 00:17:14,741
Janine. I could really use
a positive spin on my situation.

372
00:17:14,742 --> 00:17:15,952
You're screwed.

373
00:17:16,577 --> 00:17:18,787
- You are not the two, you are the...
- One.

374
00:17:18,788 --> 00:17:22,082
Girlfriend, I have
seen you handle challenges

375
00:17:22,083 --> 00:17:25,543
far more difficult
than a bunch of sixth graders.

376
00:17:25,544 --> 00:17:26,963
You got this.

377
00:17:27,964 --> 00:17:29,923
Thanks, Barb. I appreciate it.

378
00:17:29,924 --> 00:17:33,177
Hey, you wouldn't wanna take a shot
at the sixth grade this year, would you?

379
00:17:34,011 --> 00:17:35,012
[laughs]

380
00:17:35,763 --> 00:17:37,430
I'd rather retire.

381
00:17:37,431 --> 00:17:41,226
I'm so lucky to be around
such a veteran like Ms. Howard.

382
00:17:41,227 --> 00:17:44,020
- Duh. She's the greatest teacher ever.
- Right?

383
00:17:44,021 --> 00:17:46,691
I just wish I could ask her
a couple more questions.

384
00:17:47,358 --> 00:17:49,110
But I don't want to keep bothering her.

385
00:17:50,736 --> 00:17:52,195
You think maybe I could text her later?

386
00:17:52,196 --> 00:17:54,907
Oh, my God, we get it.
You have her cell phone number.

387
00:18:01,163 --> 00:18:02,164
What'd you wanna ask her?

388
00:18:02,790 --> 00:18:05,126
Ah, it's pretty basic. I just...

389
00:18:06,586 --> 00:18:08,879
Should I take roll
as soon as class starts in the morning?

390
00:18:09,547 --> 00:18:11,716
Oh, no. Ten-minute grace period.

391
00:18:12,216 --> 00:18:14,677
A lot of the kids take SEPTA.
It's a whole thing.

392
00:18:15,177 --> 00:18:17,262
I learned the hard way in my first year.

393
00:18:17,263 --> 00:18:19,806
I'm sure I'm gonna have to learn
the hard way a thousand times.

394
00:18:19,807 --> 00:18:21,683
Oh, yeah. You definitely will.

395
00:18:21,684 --> 00:18:25,854
And you're gonna wanna scream
and contemplate your life choices, and...

396
00:18:25,855 --> 00:18:27,356
it's all normal.

397
00:18:28,941 --> 00:18:31,151
If you have any more questions
and-and Barbara's busy,

398
00:18:31,152 --> 00:18:33,029
you can always just ask me.

399
00:18:34,113 --> 00:18:35,238
I appreciate that.

400
00:18:35,239 --> 00:18:36,490
It's what I'm here for.

401
00:18:37,825 --> 00:18:40,327
[Janine] <i>That is who I am now.
I don't have to be a grump.</i>

402
00:18:40,328 --> 00:18:42,579
I can be me and be a mentor.

403
00:18:42,580 --> 00:18:45,373
I'm gonna put the me in m-mentor.

404
00:18:45,374 --> 00:18:48,711
"Me-ntor." The teacher has become...

405
00:18:49,754 --> 00:18:50,755
the teacher.

406
00:18:51,255 --> 00:18:52,756
I need to get out of the sun.

407
00:18:52,757 --> 00:18:54,591
I just can't ride a bike, okay?

408
00:18:54,592 --> 00:18:57,677
Look, they say you fall down seven times,
you stand up eight.

409
00:18:57,678 --> 00:18:59,430
I gotta fall six more times?

410
00:19:00,222 --> 00:19:02,307
Hey, how's it going over here?

411
00:19:02,308 --> 00:19:04,601
- Bad.
- He's scared to get back on the bike.

412
00:19:04,602 --> 00:19:08,730
Okay, well, I could help.
I'm a brand new me. [chuckles]

413
00:19:08,731 --> 00:19:11,399
- What you mean? You sound the same.
- Oh. You missed a whole thing.

414
00:19:11,400 --> 00:19:13,902
I went through a bunch of different
personalities, landed here.

415
00:19:13,903 --> 00:19:15,820
- You still sound the same.
- Uh, I'll tell you about it later.

416
00:19:15,821 --> 00:19:17,406
- Okay.
- But, Mr. Johnson,

417
00:19:17,907 --> 00:19:22,036
I know you can ride the bike,
because I believe in you.

418
00:19:24,246 --> 00:19:25,414
I know what to do.

419
00:19:26,290 --> 00:19:28,708
Uh, everyone, stop what you're doing
right now and come over here.

420
00:19:28,709 --> 00:19:30,543
Mr. Johnson needs our help.

421
00:19:30,544 --> 00:19:33,463
No, no, please don't do that. Please.

422
00:19:33,464 --> 00:19:36,634
If we don't finish,
you have to come in on the weekend.

423
00:19:37,259 --> 00:19:39,511
You look like a guy
that loves coming in on weekends.

424
00:19:39,512 --> 00:19:42,097
Monday through Friday,
the best days of the week to you, huh?

425
00:19:42,098 --> 00:19:45,016
- No, my weekends rule.
- Yeah, okay.

426
00:19:45,017 --> 00:19:46,893
[Janine] All right, let's go, Mr. J.

427
00:19:46,894 --> 00:19:48,728
Yeah, what's the worst that could happen?

428
00:19:48,729 --> 00:19:50,021
I fall over and die.

429
00:19:50,022 --> 00:19:52,566
Well, that's just... fair.

430
00:19:53,150 --> 00:19:57,654
Look, Mr. Johnson, if you fall,
we will catch you. I promise.

431
00:19:57,655 --> 00:19:59,281
Okay? All right.

432
00:20:00,032 --> 00:20:01,700
Ready to get back up on this horse?

433
00:20:01,701 --> 00:20:04,619
Riding a horse is easy.
It's bikes I'm afraid of.

434
00:20:04,620 --> 00:20:06,747
Hey, you got this, all right?

435
00:20:07,331 --> 00:20:09,666
All right, here we go. Ready? Here...

436
00:20:09,667 --> 00:20:11,960
- [Melissa] Come on, Mr. J.
- [Janine] Go, Mr. J.

437
00:20:11,961 --> 00:20:14,046
[staff cheering]

438
00:20:17,216 --> 00:20:18,676
[Mr. Johnson] Yay!

439
00:20:19,760 --> 00:20:21,053
Yeah!

440
00:20:22,221 --> 00:20:23,514
[Melissa] Go, Mr. J!

441
00:20:24,014 --> 00:20:25,640
- Go, Mr. J!
- [cheering continues]

442
00:20:25,641 --> 00:20:28,977
Uh, I feel like we're starting
to lose focus.

443
00:20:28,978 --> 00:20:32,188
You all need to prove your virtuousness.

444
00:20:32,189 --> 00:20:33,274
Craig.

445
00:20:34,775 --> 00:20:37,653
Isn't that
what we're doing right here, huh?

446
00:20:38,946 --> 00:20:40,405
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

447
00:20:40,406 --> 00:20:44,367
Well, maybe this qualifies
as completion of team building.

448
00:20:44,368 --> 00:20:46,077
- Wait, really?
- Yes.

449
00:20:46,078 --> 00:20:48,455
Also, I have tickets
to the Ren Faire this weekend,

450
00:20:48,456 --> 00:20:50,498
- so I'm gonna need this to count.
- [scoffs]

451
00:20:50,499 --> 00:20:52,042
Okay.

452
00:20:53,210 --> 00:20:54,502
Fixed the leak.

453
00:20:54,503 --> 00:20:57,797
Good news,
killed a bunch of mice in your walls.

454
00:20:57,798 --> 00:21:00,008
Bad news, ain't my job to get rid of 'em.

455
00:21:00,009 --> 00:21:03,803
{\an8}Worst news,
I noticed you have HVAC issues.

456
00:21:03,804 --> 00:21:05,597
{\an8}You mean, like, AC and heating stuff?

457
00:21:05,598 --> 00:21:10,018
{\an8}Yep, and you're not gonna have any of that
if you don't get a specialist in here.

458
00:21:10,019 --> 00:21:11,519
{\an8}You got someone to handle this?

459
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:15,232
{\an8}Well, I'm sure Mr. Johnson's on top of it.
He's around here somewhere.

460
00:21:16,275 --> 00:21:17,275
{\an8}[Mr. Johnson screams]

461
